    "narrative": "LawDog\u2019s strongest plays today are headlined by **Lawrence Butler** (71.76) and **Tyler Freeman** (69.94). **Lawrence Butler** benefits from a massive 10% park factor boost and a favorable matchup against Jack Leiter, whose 4.43 xERA provides the right environment for **Lawrence Butler** to capitalize on his elite raw power. Meanwhile, **Tyler Freeman** holds the highest floor-to-ceiling balance due to his leadoff role against Ryan Weiss; the 7.36 xERA for Weiss is the most exploitable mark on the slate, and **Tyler Freeman**\u2019s leadoff projection provides the necessary stability to anchor the outfield. Similarly, **Cal Raleigh** (68.75) and **Brendan Donovan** (68.26) are near-elite starts; both benefit significantly from a plus-matchup against Walker Buehler, with **Brendan Donovan**\u2019s 14% platoon edge and **Cal Raleigh**\u2019s 19% SP skill advantage making them core pieces for tonight\u2019s production.\n\nThe decision-making process was tightest at the corner infield slots, where **Matt Chapman** (47.11) just missed the cut. While **Matt Chapman** offers decent power, he was pushed out by the higher upside of **Jonathan Aranda** (51.85), whose 12% platoon edge against Jordan Leasure provided enough of a statistical cushion to keep him in the starting nine. We are also monitoring the 34% rain risk in the game involving **Luis Arraez** (49.35), **Matt Chapman**, **Jung Hoo Lee**, and **Drew Gilbert**; should that contest be postponed, our bench depth will be severely tested. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** remains a high-floor staple at 67.08, bolstered by a unique \"slow delivery\" bonus from the opponent's pitcher, which significantly increases the likelihood of **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** swiping a bag\u2014an essential metric given our emphasis on the scarce stolen base category.",
